    {
      "turn_number": 22,
      "role": "persona",
      "type": "response",
      "text": "I keep replaying small moments — the day the Green Line stalled and I missed the fetal growth scan, sitting on that cold bench and just crying — because they show everything that's hard. What I want from care is simple and maybe naive: someone who notices me as a person, not a file. A midwife who asks how I'm getting here, a doctor who remembers my name and that I'm working full-time and juggling buses. Sometimes I get that — a nurse who stayed five extra minutes to explain a result — and other times appointments feel like speed-dates. The “medium risk” label makes clinicians more clinical, and I understand why, but it also makes me feel watched, anxious. I lean on apps to translate jargon because I leave appointments with more questions than answers. I wanted clear explanations, help planning how to get to the hospital, and real conversation about how this pregnancy fits into my life. That rarely happens consistently. Mostly I leave trying to hold onto the moments when someone actually listened. Those are the things that keep me going.",
      "responding_to_question_id": "Q10",
      "input_tokens": 1102,
      "output_tokens": 411
    },
